Russian President Vladimir Putin has signed a law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for violation of the time and order of payment of goods (works, services) when carrying out purchases for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve the very acute problem of non-fulfilment of their obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation where entrepreneurs could not receive payment for already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with dishonest customers who concluded unfunded contracts, tried in every way to evade the commitments made to pay and included illegal terms in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in order to protect the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment for public orders, the prosecutor’s office has submitted 9.7 thousand submissions, as a result of their consideration, 4,5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 administrative officials have been appointed to investigative bodies for organizing procedural checks, 75 materials have been submitted to them.
As a result, debts to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles were repaid.
And these huge amounts have accumulated far from being the result of the non-payment of multi-billion contracts.
Numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for far more modest amounts have led to fabulous debts.
This is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a contest for the provision of social transport services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working funds, fully fulfilled the obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial coma of debts on salaries, taxes, and loans that would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor’s office.
In a number of regions, the problem has now been leveled as much as possible.
However, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts identified by the prosecutors of the Russian Federation entities amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt indicators continue to reach critical values, the Prosecutor’s Office operates in a manual anti-crisis management mode.
The Attorney General personally holds visits with representatives of the local authorities, at which all violations disclosed by the prosecutors are dealt with and measures taken to remedy them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already been held in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg this year.
Qualitatively to improve the payment discipline of public contractors will be able to implement the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in the part of establishing the administrative responsibility of the contractor's officials for violation of the time and order of execution"
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia at the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on administrative offences with an article, which provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation of the term and procedure of payment of goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if an official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offence, then he is expected to be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the subjects of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novellas in practice.
Civil Rights Protection Group Announces Alert on Movement in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning for colored people travelling to Missouri because of discriminatory state policies and attacks on racist grounds.
The group’s statement reads as follows: “Warning for Travellers of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population, valid until August 28, 2017, calls upon all African-American travelers, guests and citizens of the state of Missouri to be especially careful and to be cautious when traveling.”
According to the National Association for the Promotion of the Progress of the Colored Population, the announcement of a warning on the movement of the group was prompted by a recently passed law in Missouri, which made it harder for people to win claims related to discrimination, as well as the fact that law enforcement representatives of the state often disproportionately choose their own.
“Your people are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of the color of their skin, they are beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the National Association for the Advancement of the Colored Population of Missouri, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization against the US state.
The group cited incidents such as the humiliation of black students on racial grounds at the University of Missouri and the death of twenty-eight-year-old Tori Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while traveling through the state, and Missouri State Police arrested him without prosecuting him for the crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri State Attorney General’s Office that the likelihood of being stopped on the road for black drivers is 75 percent higher than for white drivers.
“The goal of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri,” Chepel said.
“People need to be prepared in one way or another, whether they take the money with them for bail or tell relatives that they are traveling through the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes registered in Missouri in 2015, making the state’s 16th state in terms of such violations.
The Motion Warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which would make it more difficult to bring a case against a legal entity for housing or employment discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) announced warnings for travelers across Texas and Arizona after these states passed new immigration control laws, which required local law enforcement to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which, according to the ACLU, should have increased the number of arrests.
Movement warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
