Facebook Critics Block: You Don’t Need to Apply for a Public Position Unless You’re Ready to Hear Criticism from Voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
The Americans loved George Washington, but that didn’t stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism of course annoyed him.
He didn’t shut his mouth to his critics.
Because back in 1783, Washington said: “It is possible to take away freedom of speech and we, deaf and mute, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.”
Now I'm going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and deleted posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called the lawsuit insignificant, and the commentary on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well what."
“It’s just Facebook,” a lot of people say.
But that's important, too.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a democratic, predominantly state.
It ranks second in the approval rating among 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He demonstrated a strong hand in the management of the state and a commitment to its principles.
He also cleverly uses Facebook as a primary way of communicating with his constituents and jokingly demonstrates on his page his bald head after chemotherapy.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor’s page – which is declared as an official public forum and is run by the administration’s employees on taxpayers’ money – is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with the Washington Post, spokeswoman Amelia Chess defended the governor’s actions, claiming that blocking comments is simply their moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers and haters harassing the internet.
"Post" spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls, - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their chosen leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, substantive and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to Hogan as a Catholic.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramana from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comment section of the post.
“I also hate the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say that it’s a so-called turnaround, instead of admitting that they’re dealing with a large group of dissatisfied citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life position.”
In the era of Facebook, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is much less dusty work than it used to be when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical leads, or arresting and shutting up protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social networks.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first, pivotal decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James C. Casheris of Alexandria, the chairman of the Laudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin filed claims with the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending was about the same as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters severely overthrew his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms "Yuricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius" and "Portius" wrote letters to newspapers ridiculing Washington's decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Documents online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty on Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he did not try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech is at the very heart of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
