Poverty and Death in Indonesia's "Golden Land"
When dinner is ready, Bardina Degei doesn't use a stove.
It is rarely used even in pots.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai county in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, a housewife usually simply places a sweet potato, which here is called a “note,” right in the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is caught and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the ground floor – she has no furniture – and this is where she does her homework, such as washing clothes with cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet serves a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
The multiplicity is widespread here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are also soldiers.
“No one decides to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
This is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands quickly turned its anger against the government of Jakarta, which maintains strict control over the region, preventing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as far away as it is abandoned; the road here includes a half-hour flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, to Nabire, and then a five-hour hiring car shake.
There is no public transport here.
The city with a population of about 19,000 consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; corrugated steel roofs are painted with rust in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians arrived here, not to mention journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the papuas mee pago worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degei says, pointing at her bright, woven hand turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on the body."
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's golden land.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Pania, a highland province about the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined gold and copper for approximately $3.1 billion.
In addition, Papua can boast of forest reserves, which are estimated at $ 78 billion.
These fortunes, however, bring one misfortune to the Papua, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces maintain their suffocating presence here.
According to an investigation by the New York Times in 2005, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million, including up to $150,000 per officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuas threaten the existence of this golden age and are relentlessly suppressed.
According to human rights defenders, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and deprived of their liberty.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the mass killings of indigenous people in the highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We’ll lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – especially frequent, as claimed in another report, rape, and defeat by electric torque.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia, to Human Rights Watch.
Nuts have been delayed as Papua’s resources have attracted the influx of displaced people from other parts of Indonesia.
The province’s 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese bars, "warungi", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
Locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables at a traditional market cheaper than the natives of Papua,” explains Abet You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, for work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua – the mother-mother (women) of Papua – have lost their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as the Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights violations in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel loyal.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for the Jokes, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” Yoo said.
In fact, just two months after the inauguration of Djokovic, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas anthems at the fireplace in Enarotal, when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorcycle broke out of darkness.
The frightened children told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, the soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Aimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to the nearby government building of the electoral commission, and the next day the situation worsened.
About a thousand Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed waita, a dance of the Papua tribe mee pago: they ran around and portrayed the singing of birds.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and the military base.
When the situation got hot, internal radio soldiers were ordered: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” as it sounded, according to an official document seen by TIME magazine correspondents, but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayame, head of the Kego Koto district in Anarotali, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, calling on the crowd to disperse around the houses.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, I suddenly got a bullet in my left wrist,” he told Time magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still does not know who shot, but says the bullet flew from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
A local resident, Alfius Jou, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told Time magazine.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, Papua’s senior police inspector, told reporters that his officers were simply “protecting” their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” Pujo Sulistio, a Papua police spokesman, said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
The news of the killings reached Jakarta only the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokovi delivered a fiery speech in Jayapur, in which he expressed his condolences to the families of the victims and vowed to address the issue of historical abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation resolved immediately so that it will never happen again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would set up a non-judicial organization to end historical human rights violations.
But there were excuses almost immediately.
“Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the 1990s or early 1990s.
The fact is that we certainly want to deal with these violations, but there are procedures that need to be passed,” he said.
Viranto then gave up his words, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he did not plan to set up an organization to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be decided through a court of law.”
Viranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during the bloody vote for independence of East Timor in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua have already been resolved, including the incident in Paniaia.
The families of the victims from Paniai met with such statements with bleak mistrust.
“I have been questioned four times in the last three years, but there has been absolutely no change,” says Johannes.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
"I'm afraid I'm going to be arrested by the military, I'm afraid I'm going to be shot."
His brother Jacobus also expressed the view that the residents of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting didn't stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in Paniai district of Deiyai.
In a clash between villagers and a manager of a construction company who refused to help take a man unconscious to the hospital, one person died and another 17 were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dow, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at officers, who in response produced warning shots.
But locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were so panicked, we were afraid of retaliation,” said 29-year-old Domingu Badii, who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded hurriedly delivered.
“I’ve been at home for two days.”
The Deiyai parliament demanded that officers involved in the incident be called for an answer and a mobile police brigade recalled from the region.
Paniyai has always been a sick spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development is caused by the discontent of the Mei, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to defend the rights of the Papuas by arranging sporadic attacks and raids with abductions on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of OPM’s top executives come from Pania, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, in recent years thousands of people have been arrested and unfoundedly detained by the military under the pretext of “defence of national independence.”
Some of them never came back.
Among the population of Papua Panyai is considered a "sad, forgotten place".
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly nuts, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can take care of four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the crop for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten tuber notes are worth just 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, the economic inequality between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who arrived in large numbers after the introduction of new flights to Nabire airport, has increased.
Few existing vacancies usually come to more educated and wealthier migrants.
Papayas rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village ... because there is no work or money here,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the views of the rest of the world.
In addition, the restrictions on the work of the international media remain strict.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudy and Basil Lonshan were deported from Papua for "insufficient coherence with relevant organizations" despite being granted rare permissions to conduct the video.
According to Felim China, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, the promises made during Jokowi’s election campaign to lift restrictions on media work in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern provinces of Indonesia, Papua and Western Papua are now facing new dangers: refusals of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of media attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific states – Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands – appealed to the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the shooting in Paniai.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
A spokesman for the Indonesian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Arramanata Nasir, drew back from the group’s statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that “Indonesia still has a democratic system and there is a free press, so concealing evidence of human rights violations would be difficult.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by Dutch Human Rights Ambassador Kees Van Baar, visited Jaipur on May 4, local residents broke the silence, please: “We want freedom,” as a source who was also present at the meeting, but wished to remain unconscious.
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but the Papuas say they are unlikely to vote for Djokovic again.
“The Jokovs are a man of good intentions, but they are surrounded by those involved in the shooting in Pania,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants the Jokovs to know that the Paniai people, besides living in the shadow of a greedy army, are in poverty, and their education and health care are in a miserable state.
Gobai says that the inhabitants of Paniai, like the other papayas, consider their vote, given to Jokowi, a debt that he must pay.
“They don’t want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not allow the culprits to forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says, without raising his head.
“What else were we supposed to do?”
