EPA chief Pruitt refuses to postpone implementation of Obama-approved emission reduction rules
The day after the 15-state lawsuit, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency cancelled his decision to postpone the implementation of the Obama-approved rules aimed at reducing emissions of air pollutants and smog-producing substances.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that his agency now listens more than in previous administrations to the needs of the environmental regulators of individual states.
He did not mention the lawsuit against his previous position filed with the Federal Court of Appeal.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline, by which states must ensure compliance with 2015 ground-level ozone standards.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would postpone their compliance by one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid “discordance with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who before being appointed by President Trump to his current position, was the attorney general of the state of Oklahoma, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tightening environmental norms.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of norms opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industries.
The unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Pewitt to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the EPA overstepped his powers in an attempt to delay the Obama administration’s rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that by drastically changing the course of ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s obligation to cooperate with states in the complex process of timely implementation of new standards.
"In previous administrations, the EPA was often unable to settle on time, then waited for claims from activist groups and others, and discussed deadlines during the settlement of the case," Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen claims against the EPA in his previous post, said in a statement.
“We don’t believe in regulation through trials, and we take the deadlines seriously.
We also take our charter and the authority it gives us seriously.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could at some point again use his “authorities to postpone and other authority given by law” to make sure that the “jcyjdfys rules on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader review of the rules on ozone.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, aims to postpone compliance with the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the matter.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed a coalition of states that filed lawsuits against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA’s change of course – following our claims – is an important victory in the fight for health and safety for 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia, joined the lawsuit.
Earth-level ozone occurs when conventional pollutants from machines, power plants, oil refineries and chemical plants, and other sources, enter the atmosphere in reaction with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems in people sensitive to it, leading to thousands of premature deaths per year.
Healthcare and environmental advocates welcomed Pruitt’s sudden change of course.
“It’s hard to think about how much pressure it took to take this completely logical step from a person tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign and protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
