New test results for assessing the age of asylum seekers in Sweden published
Recent test results from asylum seekers in Sweden, who have been subjected to a new method of medical age assessment, show that more than 80 percent of the tested have been evaluated as persons over the age of 18, but not everyone trusts the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish National Agency for Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) began testing earlier this year.
They were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migrationsverket criticized it for failing to determine the actual age of some refugees who claimed to be minors.
To date, the Migrationsverket has submitted 6,880 cases for testing, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of 2,481 tests for the period between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) of those tested were assessed as being 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the Forensic Medicine Agency assessed that the person tested was “probably 18 years of age or older.”
In the case of 432 cases, the conclusion stated that the person “probably less than 18”.
Tests are only carried out in cases where the age of a person raises doubts.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results are consistent with the results of the past few months.
“We don’t see much difference with the statistics over the past months, the numbers are quite appropriate,” he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which people were assessed as over the age of 18 does not necessarily indicate that asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and reported that in 442 cases “most likely the age of 18 years or older”.
However, looking at 581 published results, the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet found that in 243 cases, the person openly stated that he was 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, consisting of x-raying wisdom teeth and tomography of the knee joints and giving them for analysis to dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some instances.
One of the skeptics is an endocrinologist from the Claude Marcus Karolinska Institutet, part of whose work is assessing the biological maturity of people to determine whether they have gone through sexual maturation earlier or later than normal.
“I had reason to think about it, and I don’t think we need to use the measurement methods that are being used now.
The biological age is thus determined very inaccurately.
If we can’t determine it with certainty, we shouldn’t pretend we can,” he told Metro.
However, Göranssen of the Forensic Medicine Agency said in favor of the accuracy of the tests: “In general, it can be said that the risk of mistakenly taking a child as an adult is small.
The greatest risk we face is when a person is soon 18, in which case he is about 10 percent.”
