These include courts, offices of heads of state bodies of entities, municipal entities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could also be ZAGS.
Those wishing to obtain Russian citizenship will take a solemn oath after officials have verified their documents.
But the Russian passport a person will receive only after making an oath, follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in from the age of 18, not from 14.
There remains a rule that those who are incapable or limited in their ability to act, as well as those who cannot pronounce, read or hand-sign the text of the oath, will be exempted from taking the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to exempt from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, the updated draft law stipulates a special procedure for receiving Russian citizens from residents of Ukraine, who are considered to be native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be transmitted to Russian officials.
A waiver of "foreign" citizenship, as it is now, will not be necessary if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is not possible "for reasons beyond personal control".
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, among which the first Deputy Speaker of DG Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Ayrat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, just impossible.
