Judges are to be protected from presidents.
The Presidential Council on Human Rights (HRC) on behalf of Vladimir Putin has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary branch of power.
The OHCHR proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their election.
For courts of appeal and cassation instances, the OHC wants to introduce special districts that will not be bound by administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
His proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate should also be submitted by the Supreme Court.
The OHCHR has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of the Russian judiciary.
This work was carried out on the orders of Vladimir Putin of January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with the members of the council.
The meeting with the members of the council on December 8, 2016 discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see "U" of December 9, 2016).
The work of the HRH resulted in 25 proposals, which concern both the independence of judges and the detection of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge has successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judiciary community, the President of the Court, in the opinion of the OHR, should submit it to the appointment, without having the right to refuse, as now allows the law.
It is also proposed to deprive the Chairperson of the right to distribute cases between judges.
To do this, experts allow, can be a specially written computer program.
Also in the HR believe that the chairman is not entitled to "prescribe the results of the qualification assessment of the judge, initiate his involvement in disciplinary responsibility, to make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments".
At the same time, the presidential council considers it necessary to move to "election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves" and "assign their powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation".
Now all the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the presentation of the president of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the OHR proposes a new way of organizing appeals and cassations in the courts of general jurisdiction.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The OHCHR says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation instances not at the level of regional judicial bodies in subjects of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts".
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
There are “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but that guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use the “telephone right”.
The OHCHR proposes to strengthen the people’s judges in order to consider some “categories of civil and administrative cases” with their participation.
For example, about deprivation of parental rights, about recovery at work, about protection of honor and dignity, about deprivation of driver's license, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained "U" member of the OHCHR, the judge of the Constitutional Court in the resignation of Tamara Morschakova.
She also recalled that the President’s mandate applied not only to the OHCHR, but also to the Supreme Court (Supreme Court), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the Air Force (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in Russia, the President of the Russian Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must by September 1.
Living a high life: a half-floor and cunning design techniques turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former banker interested in real estate repairs, moved from a spacious house in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is located on the ground floor of a cute Queen Anne style typical house, and in favor of the new design suggests that Joan has not packed her things and moved again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price on the same day.”
From the moment of the first viewing, the apartment with an area of 1000 square feet has undergone a complete reconstruction.
Initially, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-storey to get the most out of the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
For this purpose, she hired Erfan Azadi from Notting Hill’s architectural design studio “Duck & Shed” to use 12.5-foot-high ceilings and create a home that would not only be a successful project, but would suit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-story where you could stand in full growth.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms in such a way that they were one above the other, and we didn’t have to bend.
It was not just necessary to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allow the use of the rooms above and below.
This decision allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in the space allocated – and a lot more interesting.
From the semi-floor through the vintage copper light window from "Retrouvius" opens a view of the chic living room at the bottom.
Mirror furniture with a golden finish, silver accents and vintage lighting fixtures from Serge Muja set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it appear longer.
In the kitchen, a mirrored protective panel looks like a window to another room.
Mirror cabinets at the entrance serve to store all Joan's dishes.
To create a sense of more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in folding kitchens.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding door, like in a garage.
"The engineering art was involved here," Erfan will tell about the reinforced steel of the wood-fibre shield door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and improved layout.
“At the end of the day, the floor area is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued for,” Erfan says.
“Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on the floor area.”
Here they were able to increase the floor area, using quality materials that give the space a nuance of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help create an emotional connection with the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in the walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t hit the strings of our hearts.”
This serves as a testament to the fact that with a good design and increased footage, the apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you can decide to stay.
