Brothers Fight for a $500 Million Real Estate Empire
The two brothers fight for one of Victoria’s largest real estate empires worth more than $500 million — forty years after their Italian ancestors founded a dynasty.
Former director of the Carlton football club and developer Colin de Lutis lives in the Turac Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court for the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to quit the family business since 2014, but the Supreme Court is currently facing a bitter dispute over the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a shop on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans, which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the list of properties of the De Luís family today includes office buildings, construction sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller, and shopping centers in the suburbs.
By agreement with his late father, Colin - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that Colin’s property is 316 million, and Paul’s is 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
“The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property,” he wrote in his first testimony in 2015.
On Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court took place.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business – from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded him.
Colin claims that this is not true, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some facilities.
In the testimony given by Colin at the start of the trial, he says he hopes for a settlement of the dispute.
“My Italian roots make me consider the family a top priority,” he wrote.
The trial costs are growing like a snowy coma: the case involves hundreds of pages of testimonies, emails and reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer; both sides have attracted the most famous lawyers, including Royal Attorney Allan Myers, and more.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran dairy bars and gastronomers, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, where Colin opened the first family jeans store.
Colin says he started Westco when he was "in the last grades of school, and Paul was a boy then (about 10 years)."
Anna De Lutis says they and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
“Luigi has often told me that he doesn’t want the brothers to settle in court,” she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lucis group of companies; Colin says Mark received $10 million when he quit the business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were “dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their office.”
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to the 2015 biography of Eddie McGregor, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Only Colin replied with a text message that, since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing special to say."
"I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul decided to sue me and to shake our family's name in court," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in his testimony that he was trying to meet his brother's demands.
“Our father wouldn’t want to see Paul and I arguing in court,” he said, adding that he “still hopes for a settlement of the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope was shattered.
“The decision on our case will soon be taken by the court,” Colin wrote.
