Tyumen Prosecutor's Office Fights HIV Dissident
The prosecution challenged the order of the Kalinin District Court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died because the mother was an HIV-dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court acquitted her of her liability in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecution believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished in order not to set a precedent for other HIV dissidents.
The case against the resident of Tyumen was initiated under Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (cause of death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died from HIV infection in stage 4B.
According to the prosecutor’s office, the mother herself is HIV-infected.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist," the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case was brought to the Kaliningrad District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that "he pardoned his wife, has no claims to her, she smoothed the damage and apologized".
The Prosecutor ' s Office disagreed with the court ' s decision and appealed, demanding that the order to terminate the case be cancelled and referred for a new review.
The girl died, and the damage caused by the crime can not be remedied.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of the doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat her for a dangerous infection," the prosecutor's press service said.
The Authority believes that it should be punished, otherwise other HIV dissidents will follow its example.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children, suffering from HIV, do not receive medical care because of the refusal of parents.
"And this situation has already improved - in the year of work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children for HIV, changed their opinion - allowed to make a diagnosis, began to take drugs," - said the spokeswoman of the Center for AIDS Elena Loseva.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, flee with children from hospitals.
What are the dangers of HIV dissidents?
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of Russia’s first study of the so-called HIV dissident movement.
HIV dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and in their spread see a serious threat.
