Gypsies overcame the trench and returned to the "street of millionaires"
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands are once again clashing with determined gypsies who have overcome a ditch dug by municipal authorities to reoccupy the field next to their homes.
Gypsies parked 20 homes on wheels in a field bordering the rich Solihull street, which was given the joking name of “Millionaire’s Street.”
Bringing with them horses, infants and many houses on wheels, they returned after being driven out no further than in May, and they were not hindered by the trench dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their invasion.
This tactical company found a breach in the defensive structures and squeezed their vehicles through a section that was left unfenced to leave room for the trail.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihalla, saying it was "unable to solve this problem".
An anonymous local resident said: “They came here in the evening on Monday after being driven out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by.”
The municipality should be embarrassed and forced to act, because they are completely unable to solve this problem.
The Gypsies were here in May, they were driven out, and here they are again.
There were more gypsies last night, and maybe more today.
“Birmingham Municipality knows how to solve this problem, they are getting long-term court orders to protect their parks,” she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don’t like that I continue to pay municipal taxes, and the municipality can’t even put an end to that.”
One local resident, wishing to remain anonymous, said: “It’s funny, we just saw these gypsies leave the last time, and here, please, this attack continues.”
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse grazing on the meadow.”
A Solihalla Municipality spokesman said: “We are aware of an illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with Solihalla Police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them out as soon as possible.”
To help us collect evidence, it is very important that as many locals as possible report any anti-social or criminal behavior to the police by calling 101.
This makes it possible to get an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
Crimea activates the champagne factory "New World"
The SGP of the Republic of Crimea "New World Champagne Wine Plant" has decided to take action, by converting it into OJSC "New World Champagne Wine Plant", following the order of the Minister of Property and Land Relations of Crimea Anna Anyukina.
100% of the company’s shares will remain in the state ownership of Crimea.
The registered capital of the joint-stock company will be 595.5 million rubles and will consist of 5.955 million ordinary shares with a nominal value of 100 rubles each.
The Ministry of Agriculture of Crimea stated that if within the next three years there are no funds for the modernization of the enterprise, there will be a threat of stopping the plant.
The wear and tear of the capital at the enterprise is about 60-70%.
The modernization of the enterprise requires 1.2 billion rubles. Due to the peculiarities of the organizational and legal form, it is obliged to give 50% of the profit to the income of the budget.
What remains is not enough to implement the modernization plan.
"Getting money from the owner is problematic, talking about attracting loan funds from large credit organizations is difficult," Deputy Head of the Ministry of Crimea Sergey Petelin said in April this year.
The Crimean Parliament has included the company in the planned privatization plan for 2017.
It was proposed to hold its shares and put up for auction.
The source of "Interfax" in the authorities of Crimea estimated the possible cost of the sale of the enterprise at $40 million, the investment of the investor in the modernization - another $30 million.
“New World” in 2016 increased the production of sparkling wines by 2.8% compared to the level of 2015 - to 1.52 million bottles.
In 2017, New World planned to release 1.6 million bottles.
The company was founded in 1878 by Prince Lvov Golitsyn as a plant for the production of sparkling wine in the Noviy Svet estate he acquired.
The plant is located on 11 hectares of land.
