Italy is tightening the tone for NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned NGOs who own rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
"If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities," Interior Minister Mario Minniti told the daily newspaper Stampa in Turin.
Minniti’s warning came the day after Italian authorities confiscated a ship owned by German humanitarian organisation Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which had only worked for a year, declined to comment on the substantive details of the charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"For us, saving human lives is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue to work in the search and rescue zone right now," the organization said in a statement.
“We will only be able to assess all the accusations made now, once we have gathered all the information and are able to assess the situation.”
The Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventus vessel belonging to Jugend Rettet since October.
His crew is suspected of taking on board entire lifeboats of migrants, which human traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing smugglers to leave along with boats that they could reuse.
At least one such meeting is expected to take place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the allegations, the contents of which were published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the regulations of the Italian coastal authorities, who control rescue operations in the area, rather out of humanitarian zeal than for any other reason.
The Code of Conduct mainly envisages that Juventus-type vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to abide by the code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Expanded Hugs from Spain.
She said on Thursday that she considers the new rules unnecessary, but acceptable, provided they do not cause any "significant changes or disruptions" to her rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Meanwhile, Minniti said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coast guard and cooperation with local mayors are bearing fruit.
“In recent days we have started to see light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He reported on plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving these countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
