You and Haftar talked.
Does the fact that he studied twice in the USSR facilitate mutual understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level?
And, by the way, does Haftar speak Russian?
Russian, if he knows, is very relative.
But what he learned from us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
And not just with him, by the way.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Missouri, we meet generals who have studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And here they are, they speak Russian very well.
And they tend to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you believe that the immediate lifting of the arms embargo on Libya is likely?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in delivering Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have said, we do not occupy the side of anyone in this conflict and do not want to arm some to the detriment of others.
We would like everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As far as the arms embargo is concerned, the Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow facilitate its lifting.
The process of drafting a constitution is now actively advancing in Libya.
We hope that the parties will come to compromise solutions, an internal consensus will be reached.
Then the elections should be held, as was said at the meeting of Sarajevo and Haftar.
If the elections take place and the legitimate power is finally elected (and now neither side has such a status), then the question of lifting the arms embargo can be asked in the UN Council.
To raise this question now is meaningless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of floating African refugees from Libya, feels abandoned by allies of the EU.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar’s forces will take control of the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers moving immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on this.
The Italians need the support of Russia, because Moscow is in dialogue at the same time with Haftar, with Sarajevo, with Missouri and with the south of the country.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a major role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the Southerners interrupting the flows of migrants on long-distance approaches?
