Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these streams going.
We hope to help bring the South together in the negotiating process between Sarajevo, Haftar and the tribes of the South.
But first, we would like to see unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarajevo.
The head of government in Tripoli, Faiz Saraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical do you think he is?
Will this not be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion about him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But there are Islamists in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country – moderately Islamic, open to the world.
He is also actively fighting against terrorists.
Why does he have such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, there is legislative, executive and judicial power.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not going there.
And we mixed all the maps and began to actively communicate with both Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
The Director of NOC Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin concluded the deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of the Libyan oil company Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I guess I'll re-sell.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
It plans to re-sign the contracts signed under Muammar Gaddafi.
We are talking, in particular, about the previous agreements in the field of transport (railway construction), energy (electricity) and a number of others.
Do the Libyans have anything to pay for?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, it is about the scheme of “oil in exchange for services”?
I do not know what the scheme will be, directly I do not deal with these issues.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are, in fact, doing peacekeeping work there.
For us, the most important thing is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans come to terms with each other so that they can establish order and Libya ceases to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is precisely the main task - to help the Libyan people and to expel terrorists from there.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or earlier) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to find out.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date no one from Russia and other countries of the former USSR is there.
He said that he has about 50,000 recordings of phone calls from representatives of Islamist and radical groups (in Libya - "U") and the Russian language does not sound there.
Which states are these militants from?
I would not like to go into that detail.
Let’s formulate the question differently.
How many of the Islamist militants in Libya are Libyans themselves?
There are practically no Libyans among them, no more than 5%.
The rest are foreigners.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
There are plans like that.
We are in active talks with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and have said that they are ready to come again - to Moscow or to Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to say now.
Several visits are yet to take place, and I hope that there will be clarity about the time and place of the negotiations.
