Michelle Carter Convicted of Reporting Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman was sentenced to two and a half years in prison for inciting her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide by texting and calling.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months in prison and another five years in probation.
Carter was convicted in June of the unintentional murder of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at the hearing Thursday: “My family is saddened.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at liberty until appeal.
She was threatened with a maximum term of 20 years, but her lawyers said she and Roy both suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, squeezing her hands and lowering her eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy with her actions," the prosecutor told the court.
“She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
"She didn't show any remorse."
But attorney Carter said it was “a tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that he believed her "age, maturity, or even mental illness did not noticeably affect her actions."
The prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother, Lynn Roy, saying: "No day has passed that I would not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I am doing – I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will remain with us forever.”
Sister Roya Camdin Roy said she was insecurely haunted by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunts of his children.
“To lose a man who has been with me ever since I was born is a pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
This case appears to be a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide for the responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case drew the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been pushed to suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang up, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know there are many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote, “You have to do this, Conrad” and “You just have to turn on the ignition, and you will be free and happy.”
Judge Monis said Carter wanted to get attention through Roy’s death, and forbade her from communicating with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of the murder in Italy of her British apartment neighbor and acquitted two years later.
30-year-old Knox published her own opinion in the Los Angeles Times, claiming that "Michele Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
