Audi to Modify Up to 850,000 Diesel Cars
The day before the announcement, BMW said it would offer to update the software for more than 350,000 cars.
BMW’s chairman said the company believes there are “more intelligent roads than driving restrictions,” referring to European cities – including Munich, where BMW is located – that have been considering banning or limiting the use of diesel cars.
Daimler said on Thursday it would modify three million Mercedes cars in Europe to reduce their diesel emissions.
None of the companies called their move a recall.
European automakers have actively promoted the use of diesel cars in Europe and the United States to promote compliance with carbon emissions regulations.
But nitrogen oxides that are emitted by diesel engines are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost for car manufacturers to install equipment that neutralizes diesel car exhaust is also rising, and maintaining a competitive price for cars becomes difficult.
While German automakers are under close scrutiny, Chancellor Angela Merkel’s government has also been accused of inciting influential automakers and ignoring signs of the problem.
The companies try not to repeat the mistake of the Volkswagen, which concealed the use of so-called “defeat devices”, which during testing could correct the amount of harmful gases emitted to comply with the rules, and under normal driving conditions turned off.
In the United States, several Volkswagen executives have been convicted and others are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, a former head of the thermodynamics department of the Audi engine development team was arrested in Germany.
The former manager, Zacqueo Giovanni Pamio, is Italian and therefore unprotected from extradition and may be tried in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi came under German criminal investigation involving Volkswagen after authorities accused Audi of installing a system to circumvent European emission rules and expanded the investigation, which had previously focused on the United States.
The inclusion of Audi in the investigation can create serious problems for Volkswagen: the manufacturer of luxury cars is a source of disproportionately large share of Volkswagen’s income.
