Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, though terrifying.
The researchers said the first remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner survived so well that experts called it “Mona Lisa among the dinosaurs.”
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his flaky skin was reddish-brown – and say that he had, in a way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as “the best-preserved of the Tyreophore in history and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
This fossil is a recently found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
