"It's only worth a little bit of squatting, and you can almost believe that he's sleeping," said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology, where the creation is being demonstrated.
“He will enter the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs – Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
By examining its skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite the fact that it was covered with an armor and resembled a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerfully armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective paint, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow him to merge with the environment faster and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, assuming he was hunted by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaurus family, was widely featured in the press in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum lab worker Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group who spent more than 7,000 hours on its meticulous excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the shells and armor plates on his body.
They found a protective color, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its bottom.
Although protective dyeing is common, the discovery was a surprise because the size of the dinosaur Borealopelta significantly exceeds the size of the now-living animals with protective dyeing.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern protective-colored animals—such as deer, zebras, or armored vehicles—are much smaller and more affordable prey, indicating that nodosaurus had to seriously fight for survival.
“The serious threat from predators to a massive, powerful dinosaur armor shows how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were,” Brown said.
The chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the dinosaur’s peel also suggests that its skin was supposed to be reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about his life, including the preserved contents of his digestive tract, to find out what he ate during his last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into a river and was taken to the sea, where it sank and lay back down to the bottom of the ocean.
At the time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans were likely to spread much further into the depths of the land than they are now.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with the remaining peeled skin, and at the same time has been fully preserved in three dimensions, while preserving the original shape of the animal,” Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, it’s just a little bit of a trick, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
