What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next nearly three years became the subject of a new documentary film, Whose Streets?, to be released on screen on August 11.
It is a story about survival and protest, about love and loss, strength and resilience from the point of view of people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrell was on her way to Ferguson with her daughter dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of color, they remembered a conversation that had led to that morning countless times, “about the experience of the blacks and their situation.”
She recalls saying, “Remember how I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
“We’re going to Ferguson now because a police officer killed an eighteen-year-old boy, and that was wrong.”
“I couldn’t help but take it,” Ferrell later said.
“What’s happening today is the culmination of what happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and be educated about it.
It must not only understand activism and organization well, but also understand the different levels of experience of blacks and their positions and what we must do to become free in order to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she herself will not face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
