Appearance of similarity: artist creates portraits with the help of Chelsea Manning DNA
In the center of the hall in the Friedman Gallery in New York from the ceiling on the wire hanging faces of people - white, black and brown, all something elusively similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek sweeps and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent clippings from the prison of Fort Levenworth, where the former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for the famous transmission of confidential diplomatic telegrams on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which closed on August 2, is called “The Emergence of Similarity”.
This is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and famous dissident whom Barack Obama softened his sentence just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing the DNA obtained from Manning's computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a profound, though not easy to perceive, manifesto of the non-DNA data, not only about the plasticity of their DNA, but also about the differential between them.
Manning, who was born with the name Bradley Edward, but since adolescence has openly said she considers herself a woman, was convicted of 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her photographs in prison were unavailable, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie on which Manning in a platinum-toned wig, clearly feeling embarrassed, sat behind the wheel of the car; with this photograph she began to be associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as smokes and chewing gum, emitting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people might look like.
And then she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some kind of portrait to illustrate the article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at the preliminary screening of the new press exhibition.
Chelsea could not be visited and photographed at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait made from her DNA.
In such an unusual way, the artist and her prison muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters for two years.
They even wrote a comic book "Suppressed Images" illustrated by Shoeley Canungo, which depicted how in the future the president would mitigate Chelsea's punishment and allow her to attend the exhibition in person.
That Obama really decided to release Manning just a few days after the book was released was a pleasant surprise after seven difficult years in the Kansas military prison.
There’s something deep and strong about the show being opened right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people revealing secret information to the government, and invents new ways to fuel the enmity he’s meant to mitigate on Twitter.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this over time, she said that "coincidence does not happen".
In a statement written on the gallery wall, Manning’s huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a point above the “i” in her surname) calls for an end to “automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is her mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of pencil C, G and A.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist exquisitely expresses herself), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how surprisingly similar we all are, at least in our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not define what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is," Dewey-Harborg said; her 2007 video work, Fake Memories, is also featured here.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exhibition, which fits in one room, is the above-mentioned comic book novel.
On it, a King-Kong Manning appears above the U.S. Correctional Barracks building with a loudspeaker in hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
“Never be silent.”
“This is a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,” says the artist, welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still have ants on my skin when I talk about it."
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person – as it was cleverly depicted in the comics – but when it arrives, it will be greeted by masks in the middle of the room, its own genomic simulators, gathered like crowds of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, like everything at the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning's height), on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn by pencil.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I wanted them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that was formed around Chelsea, like the movement that was behind her liberation.”
