Startups that will help your company not to become the next “Uber”
Amy Errett wanted to assess the level of satisfaction among employees of her e-commerce startup, but the surveys did not work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs a 75-person, San Francisco-based e-commerce company called Madison Reed.
He then turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of start-ups in the field of work with staff that help companies find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to make express enquiries, address specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases, allow whistleblowers to contact them.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City’s Glint startup, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she has gained a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over three years of using Glint.
In addition to the express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a company thermal map and shows in a visual form which units have the most complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, allowing it to understand why.
Companies are slowly realizing that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become the next “Uber”, which was implicated in the scandal when a former employee posted a blog post describing an aggressive situation in which those who expressed dissatisfaction were punished.
For startups like Glint, it’s a desire to control the situation – an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to estimates by the Internet portal Let’s Talk about Payments, dedicated to financial technology, the global governance, regulation and compliance industry could cost more than $118.7 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year against the backdrop of Uber’s reputation dropping.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send custom-made staff opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real time, and view thermal maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The public opinion court seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company is mishandling employees or behaving unethically, even if the inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of customer boycotts, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a network of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for over a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures, and to offer an easy way to contact the company’s headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or a head office email, file a formal complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and awkward experience, said James Vitrano, the head of Ruby Tuesday’s law firm, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Convercent service, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be quickly detected and addressed.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday network’s risk management team.
“And we protect our shareholders from lawsuits with employees.”
According to Quinland, the companies began to take employees’ ethics, values, and engagement more seriously in 2002, after Arthur Andersen’s accounting firm collapsed due to ethical breaches as a result of the Enron Cases.
But it wasn’t until “social media got massively spread” that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty underwear from viral spreading online.
“Before using technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for the use of their products.
This is a business model and an opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, resulting in the company’s total capital of $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than they used to.
In fiercely competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects, this is just the minimum required.
Employees want to feel that they are welcomed and appreciated, and that they dedicate their time to the company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy to work at a company, they feel that they are being heard and that the work they do brings results, they are more trying to make such a company successful,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where Converlincent and LinkedIn are also used.
Investors earn income when the business of companies from their portfolio is going well; the business of companies is going well when employees are committed and involved.
If third-party analytical tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to the experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company’s trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it can create the impression that changes are coming.
And if the changes don’t come quickly enough, or don’t come at all, disappointment may develop, and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you should be prepared to have 4,000 interviews,” says Russell Rat, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, which has had to see companies make a mistake by relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go to the end, the employees will say, ‘Did you really hear me?
You don't care?
And if you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after gathering feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision making and quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long term, this knowledge will help it to retain employees more effectively in an industry known for its high workforce flow.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you’ll lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
If you lose customers, you lose companies.
