Create a comic book: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, Scotty's tiny castle was filmed in the music video "Squeeze", and in the 1970s and 80s served as a harbour for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy spot in the Bull River Valley in Kent, he watched the tumultuous history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with a land hair and a tendency to historical documents, for a novel-comic book.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says with enthusiasm.
“You feel so personal when you hold that letter in your hand.”
"The Castle in England" spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells about families who lived in Scotland; each story illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkevich, Brian May Smith, William Axley, Becky Isle.
This is not Rhodes’ first book, which is based on archival data: in 2014, he wrote “Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories” – a collection of documents from the British Library; this project unexpectedly touched him to the depths of his soul.
“I could have just been fingerprinted on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
"This is his fingerprint."
And the letters always smell like smoke, because at that time the lights were lit.
And in 300 years, in the future, you feel like you're there, too.
"I love the archives!"
For a person so passionate about old papers, getting support from the National Foundation and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months ("To be honest, I've been a little over there") seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent all day studying the "new" Victorian castle, walking through the archives and looking at the numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of the hyenas on the walls or bottles, centuries lying in the ditch.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners and sometimes artists working on illustrations of his book.
Then at night he “drank whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of Scotty Castle is not very well understood, because the National Fund received full access to it only in 2006, when the last heir, Elizabeth Hassey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were only beginning to deal with the archives, which he describes as “something that the aristocrats have thrown down on the attic for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the times of the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: "You think land disputes are boring," says Rhodes, "but two families fought for this birch.
That's how it is, guys!"
In some of the collection's stories, the castle becomes a starting point for broader discoveries in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is information about a rebellion that took place in the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex,” Rhodes says.
“The peasant uprising began in these places, and I thought the uprising was a proper beginning.
“Maybe they were tied up?”
Other plots are closely related to the castle's history - for example, "The Priest", which tells about a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
