However, the information "U" was officially confirmed in the GKNPC.
He decided to move to the post of Director of Production Coordination, - they said at the enterprise. - Andrey Okhlopkov, the task set before him to provide a launch minimum for the first launch on the Eastern spacecraft fully fulfilled.
Mr. Ochlopkov moved to work at the CENKI in 2013, having a service in the space forces, in particular in Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - on the "northern" cosmodrome held the position of the first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrey Okhlopkov became a figurehead in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, from his submission, regional merchants received state orders for retaliation, but did not comply with the commitments made to clean up the detached parts of the carrier missiles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Republic of Komi.
In 2012, the jury found him innocent.
The responsibilities for technological development entrusted to him in CENKI were extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of the cosmodrome in the Far East.
The then head of the Federal Space Agency, Oleg Ostapenko, in an interview with "U" said that the situation in the East "was critical already in October 2013".
The fact is that during the planning, a strategic error was made: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 carrier rocket were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch by the end of the year, the construction was decided six months earlier and the deadlines were moved from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, we had to go through a trick: CENI specialists began to conduct parallel installation of technological equipment on unfinished facilities.
The main proponent of this idea was Andrey Okhlopkov.
Despite the risks and still the transfer (instead of December 2015 "Soyuz" flew only on April 28, 2016), this idea was justified, says the source "U" on the spacecraft: "Otherwise, we would not have made a single launch from the East, but would have engaged in construction".
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who supervised the creation of the cosmodrome, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his "Space Susanin", but it was he who almost always asked for information about the progress of the construction.
