Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate can help alleviate BPH.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to alleviate symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington have found that the main amino acid protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explained that the immune cells in the intestines make sure that the harmful microbes that come with food do not penetrate the body.
Cells capable of triggering the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body and not harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too severely disturbed towards inflammation, it can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacteria in the intestine have increased cell tolerance.
And this bacteria needs tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: "We have established a link between one species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a tolerance-enhancing cell population.
The more tryptophan was contained in the mice’s diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less prone to inflammation in the intestine.
Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of mice had these cells and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but were contained separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by mice’s gut microbiomes — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that typically live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice’s gut cell DNA was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice with immune cells but absent in mice without them.
Mice raised in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid environment and then transferred small portions of the fluid — without bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells secreted from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of the processing of tryptophan, known as indol-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the level of tryptophan was reduced by half, the number of cells also dropped by twice.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have as much cell tolerance as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans as much as in mice, but defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases.
She says: “It’s possible that we need to strengthen the development of these cells, because inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines depend on these cells.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an increase in their population."
