Requisite for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to the Armed Forces records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to drive a naval helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as “Marine One” when the president is on board, became the central element of the event held on July 17 in the White House, which demonstrated American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials surveyed tech products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, produced in Connecticut, was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Squadron of Marine Helicopters (HMX-1), the department responsible for the control of the helicopter, the Military Department of the White House ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or "FRAGO", just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Pole.
“I just wanted you to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually widely reported event in the press,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his chief, the first deputy chief of aviation for the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive at the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 a.m. and stay there until the lawn is released between 6 and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight in accordance with the hours of work restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit's security personnel remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records received by TIME magazine, it remains unclear whether a second crew was required as a result.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, the HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicts this decision.
“Among other things, we asked if this was a violation of Hatch’s law, and we were told that it was not,” the commander wrote.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act did not apply to it.
But even the official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to promote health care reform, which was then in the process of being drafted in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is unlikely to be a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But requesting them only in the interests of photography is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when a presidential plane went into the background during his first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was flooded with complaints about his predecessor’s use of the presidential plane.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, deputy White House spokeswoman.
The HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the transport of the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of up to an inch.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, the HMX-1 conducted 58 training runs at the White House.
According to one of the officials, the flight, made for the event "Made in America", was counted to the crew at the expense of the necessary training flights for a month.
Helicopters of the unit on that day also encountered 11 additional hours as part of "non-presidential support tasks".
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of the company "Sikorsky" reported that the company did not participate in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not take into account the budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the hourly rates of the Ministry of Defense for the 2017 fiscal year, the rate of reimbursement of the Ministry of Defense for VH-3D is $ 24,380 per hour of flight.
The unit's records recorded that the aircraft's time in the air was 30 minutes in each direction from its airfield based at the Quantico Marine Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the actual cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Calculating the cost for taxpayers based on the approximate rate of reimbursement is completely wrong,” says Walters.
“These approximate rates include staffing, service, and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but, indeed, take into account the cost of fuel, service and expenses specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase this week the things that have been done in America,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
So, of course, it’s important to pay attention to that.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was exactly in the driver’s seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump appealed to representatives of the Sikorsky company, joking with the press about his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky well,” the president said.
